NAME - ::<namespace>:: emulation_ldp_config

DESCRIPTION

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT, IxNetwork-NGPF

This procedure configures LDP simulated routers and the router interfaces.

SYNOPSIS - ::<namespace>::emulation_ldp_config

List arguments in the alphabetical order or in the reverse alphabetical order.

ARGUMENTS

[M] indicates if the argument is mandatory on the supported platform.

-handle

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

A LDP handle returned from this procedure and now being used when the -mode is anything but create.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

A LDP handle returned from this procedure and now being used when the -mode is anything but create. When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology.

DEFAULT

 None

-mode

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork [M] , IxOS/IxNetwork-FT [M]

DESCRIPTION

Which mode is being performed. All but create require the use of create - Create a new LDP routermodify - Modify an existing LDP routerdelete - Delete the given LDP routerdisable - Disable the given LDP routerenable - Enable the given LDP router

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

Which mode is being performed. All but create require the use of the -handle option.

Valid options are:

create

Create a new LDP router

delete

Delete the given LDP router

disable

Disable the given LDP router

enable

Enable the given LDP router

modify

Modify an existing LDP router

DEFAULT

 None

-port_handle

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork [M] , IxOS/IxNetwork-FT [M]

DESCRIPTION

The port which on which the LDP configuration will take place.

DEFAULT

 None

-label_adv

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

The mode by which the simulated router advertises its FEC ranges. unsolicited - (default) The router distributes FEC ranges whenever it has a new one.on_demand - The router only distributes FEC ranges when requested by a peer.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

The mode by which the simulated router advertises its FEC ranges.

Valid options are:

unsolicited

(default) The router distributes FEC ranges whenever it has a new one.

on_demand

The router only distributes FEC ranges when requested by a peer.

DEFAULT

unsolicited

-peer_discovery

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

link - (default) The basic mode which does not attempt to contact targeted peers.targeted - Attempts to contact targeted peers.targeted_martini - Attempts to contact targeted peers.

DEFAULT

 None

-interface_handle

Supported platforms Details

-interface_mode

Supported platforms Details

IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

Valid only for IxTclProtocol API (old API).When -mode is modify, if you provide layer 2-3 protocol configuration parameters (-intf_ip_addr, -gateway_ip_addr, -loopback_ip_addr etc), if parameter -interface_mode is set to "add", a new interface will be added to the existing one. If -interface_mode is set to "modify", the last interface of the LDP router will be modified.(DEFAULT = "modify")

DEFAULT

modify

-intf_ip_addr

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

Interface IP address of the LDP session router. Mandatory when -mode is create. When using IxTclNetwork (new API) this parameter can be omitted if -interface_handle is used.For IxTclProtocol (old API), when -mode is modify and one of the layer 2-3 parameters (-intf_ip_addr, -gateway_ip_addr, -loopback_ip_addr, etc) needs to be modified, the emulation_ldp_config command must be provided with the entire list of layer 2-3 parameters. Otherwise they will be set to their default values.

DEFAULT

0.0.0.0

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

Interface IP address of the LDP session router. Mandatory when -mode is create. When using IxTclNetwork (new API) this parameter can be omitted if -interface_handle is used. For IxTclProtocol (old API), when -mode is modify and one of the layer 2-3 parameters (-intf_ip_addr, -gateway_ip_addr, -loopback_ip_addr, etc) needs to be modified, the emulation_ldp_config command must be provided with the entire list of layer 2-3 parameters. Otherwise they will be set to their default values.

DEFAULT

0.0.0.0

-vlan_id_step

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

Valid only for -mode create. Defines the step for the VLAN ID when the VLAN ID mode is increment.When vlan_id_step causes the vlan_id value to exceed its maximum value the increment will be done modulo .Examples: vlan_id = 4094; vlan_id_step = 2 -> new vlan_id value = 0vlan_id = 4095; vlan_id_step = 11 -> new vlan_id value = 10

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

Valid only for -mode create. Defines the step for the VLAN ID when the VLAN ID mode is increment. When vlan_id_step causes the vlan_id value to exceed its maximum value the increment will be done modulo . Examples: vlan_id = 4094; vlan_id_step = 2 -> new vlan_id value = 0 vlan_id = 4095; vlan_id_step = 11 -> new vlan_id value = 10

DEFAULT

1

-reconnect_time

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

(in milliseconds) This Fault Tolerant (FT) Reconnect Timer value is advertised in the FT Session TLV in the Initialization message sent by a neighbor LSR. It is a request sent by an LSR to its neighbor(s) - in the event that the receiving neighbor detects that the LDP session has failed, the receiver should maintain MPLS forwarding state and wait for the sender to perform a restart of the control plane and LDP protocol. If the value = 0, the sender is indicating that it will not preserve its MPLS forwarding state across the restart. If -graceful_restart_enable is set.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

(in milliseconds) This Fault Tolerant (FT) Reconnect Timer value is advertised in the FT Session TLV in the Initialization message sent by a neighbor LSR. It is a request sent by an LSR to its neighbor(s) - in the event that the receiving neighbor detects that the LDP session has failed, the receiver should maintain MPLS forwarding state and wait for the sender to perform a restart of the control plane and LDP protocol. If the value = 0, the sender is indicating that it will not preserve its MPLS forwarding state across the restart. If -graceful_restart_enable is set.

DEFAULT

 None

-recovery_time

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

If -graceful_restart_enable is set; (in milliseconds) The restarting LSR is advertising the amount of time that it will retain its MPLS forwarding state. This time period begins when it sends the restart Initialization message, with the FT session TLV, to the neighbor LSRs (to re-establish the LDP session). This timer allows the neighbors some time to resync the LSPs in an orderly manner. If the value = 0, it means that the restarting LSR was not able to preserve the MPLS forwarding state.

DEFAULT

 None

NOTES

IxNetwork-NGPF

Coded versus functional specification. If one wants to modify the ineterface to which the protocol interface is connected, one has to specify the correct MAC address of that interface. If this requirement is not fulfilled, the interface is not guaranteed to be correctly determined because more interfaces can have the exact same configuration. When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology. reconnect_time

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

(in milliseconds) This Fault Tolerant (FT) Reconnect Timer value is advertised in the FT Session TLV in the Initialization message sent by a neighbor LSR. It is a request sent by an LSR to its neighbor(s) - in the event that the receiving neighbor detects that the LDP session has failed, the receiver should maintain MPLS forwarding state and wait for the sender to perform a restart of the control plane and LDP protocol. If the value = 0, the sender is indicating that it will not preserve its MPLS forwarding state across the restart. If -graceful_restart_enable is set.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

(in milliseconds) This Fault Tolerant (FT) Reconnect Timer value is advertised in the FT Session TLV in the Initialization message sent by a neighbor LSR. It is a request sent by an LSR to its neighbor(s) - in the event that the receiving neighbor detects that the LDP session has failed, the receiver should maintain MPLS forwarding state and wait for the sender to perform a restart of the control plane and LDP protocol. If the value = 0, the sender is indicating that it will not preserve its MPLS forwarding state across the restart. If -graceful_restart_enable is set.

DEFAULT

 None

recovery_time

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

If -graceful_restart_enable is set; (in milliseconds) The restarting LSR is advertising the amount of time that it will retain its MPLS forwarding state. This time period begins when it sends the restart Initialization message, with the FT session TLV, to the neighbor LSRs (to re-establish the LDP session). This timer allows the neighbors some time to resync the LSPs in an orderly manner. If the value = 0, it means that the restarting LSR was not able to preserve the MPLS forwarding state.

DEFAULT

 None

IxNetwork-NGPF

DESCRIPTION

This time period begins when it sends the restart Initialization message, with the FT session TLV, to the neighbor LSRs (to re-establish the LDP session). This timer allows the neighbors some time to resync the LSPs in an orderly manner. If the value = 0, it means that the restarting LSR was not able to preserve the MPLS forwarding state.

IxNetwork-NGPF

Coded versus functional specification. If one wants to modify the ineterface to which the protocol interface is connected, one has to specify the correct MAC address of that interface. If this requirement is not fulfilled, the interface is not guaranteed to be correctly determined because more interfaces can have the exact same configuration. When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology. If the current session or command was run with -return_detailed_handles 0 the following keys will be omitted from the command response: handle

reconnect_time

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

(in milliseconds) This Fault Tolerant (FT) Reconnect Timer value is advertised in the FT Session TLV in the Initialization message sent by a neighbor LSR. It is a request sent by an LSR to its neighbor(s) - in the event that the receiving neighbor detects that the LDP session has failed, the receiver should maintain MPLS forwarding state and wait for the sender to perform a restart of the control plane and LDP protocol. If the value = 0, the sender is indicating that it will not preserve its MPLS forwarding state across the restart. If -graceful_restart_enable is set.

DEFAULT

 None

recovery_time

Supported platforms Details

IxNetwork, IxOS/IxNetwork-FT

DESCRIPTION

If -graceful_restart_enable is set; (in milliseconds) The restarting LSR is advertising the amount of time that it will retain its MPLS forwarding state. This time period begins when it sends the restart Initialization message, with the FT session TLV, to the neighbor LSRs (to re-establish the LDP session). This timer allows the neighbors some time to resync the LSPs in an orderly manner. If the value = 0, it means that the restarting LSR was not able to preserve the MPLS forwarding state.

NOTES

IxNetwork-NGPF

Coded versus functional specification. If one wants to modify the ineterface to which the protocol interface is connected, one has to specify the correct MAC address of that interface. If this requirement is not fulfilled, the interface is not guaranteed to be correctly determined because more interfaces can have the exact same configuration. When -handle is provided with the /globals value the arguments that configure global protocol setting accept both multivalue handles and simple values. When -handle is provided with a a protocol stack handle or a protocol session handle, the arguments that configure global settings will only accept simple values. In this situation, these arguments will configure only the settings of the parent device group or the ports associated with the parent topology. If the current session or command was run with -return_detailed_handles 0 the following keys will be omitted from the command response: handle
